{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"681b8179-b19a-4836-a52c-07dade11519e","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a built-in .NET MAUI `ContentPage` property — that's likely why it has no effect. You need platform-specific configuration for each OS:\n\n**XAML — iOS safe area opt-out:**\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**Android — draw behind system bars** (in `MainActivity.cs`):\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n    // Draw content behind status bar & navigation bar\n    AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n    Window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n    Window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n}\n```\n\n> **Note:** On Android 15+ (API 35), edge-to-edge is enforced automatically, but you still need the transparent bar colors. On older API levels, `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false)` is what opts you in.\n\n**Key points:**\n- **iOS**: `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` is the correct property.\n- **Android**: It's a window-level setting, not a XAML property.\n- Use `Aspect=\"AspectFill\"` on the `Image` so it fills without letterboxing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ff5bebfb-c64f-45bf-b289-04a3735232e9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI full-screen/edge-to-edge display. They want an image to go behind the status bar and navigation bar, filling the entire screen. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common issue in .NET MAUI. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n1. `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` is not a standard .NET MAUI property on ContentPage. The user might be confusing iOS safe area concepts.\n\n2. In .NET MAUI, to go edge-to-edge, you typically need to:\n   - On Android: Configure the status bar and navigation bar to be transparent, and use edge-to-edge display settings\n   - On iOS: Disable safe area insets using platform-specific properties\n\nFor newer .NET MAUI versions, the approach varies by platform. On iOS, you'd use `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"false\"` to ignore safe areas, while Android requires configuring the window appearance and potentially using edge-to-edge APIs depending on the Android version. Setting up the XAML structure with the proper namespace declarations for iOS platform-specific configuration, then I'll show the actual implementation for handling edge-to-edge display on both platforms. I'm realizing I need to reconsider the approach here. `SafeAreaEdges` might not be a standard ContentPage property—it could be from a third-party library or a misunderstanding. The clearer path is using `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` on iOS and handling edge-to-edge display through platform-specific configuration on Android, though the exact APIs and defaults have shifted across .NET versions.","outputTokens":1656,"requestId":"1433:AAEEE:2FBC5A:36AF74:6A03CF3C"},"id":"c573b327-6fab-4417-98d6-6d94f092b2d5","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:09:49.637Z","parentId":"c92f2f7c-0d23-4f98-96ac-24e1ee9d2c92"}
